ng journalism has become fraudulent. So now we have a person insisting families who place their children in a failing Public School System are bad and uncaring people.   I attended private parochial schools (not catholic), from elementary to high school, until our family moved. I was a sophomore, ended up in a very good public school, yet overcrowding in class rooms and lazy unenthused Teachers was the second part of the problem for me. Then the fact I was 2 to 3 years ahead in the required classes I attended. The biggest adjustment admittedly was social adjustment. After all, I went from growing and learning with the same kids for 11 years! My public high school had a graduating class of 479 Students!   I watched my peers in college struggle with the structure and discipline I was fortunate enough to be taught and ended up tutoring several of my public school peers, as well as offering support Not to give up due to the frustrations of the unpreparedness the Public School failed too. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1302" language="en" documentId="2888" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Sonmi-451" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:05PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2888" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1302"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>